# TFLITE Conversion

Without conversion, raw keras model has all model parameters (weights, activations, biases) stored as float32
There is a hybrid model conversion, where no dataset is provided during conversion, but optimization is configured 
where only weights are converted to int8. This means that size of model is reduced from 4B to 1B per weight. During
inference this value is converted back to float and calculation is done with FPA since activations and biases are not converted.
Activations  can be converted only if dataset is provided during conversion with values that represent the ranges 
of inputs that are valid for the model. Biases do not need directly inputs in order to be quantized, but their quantizaiton
is calculated based on input activation scale and weight scale, so without quantized activations biases also cannot be quantized.

## Quantization Scheme Scaling
Because int8 can store whole numbers between -128-127 the converter creates a linear formula to map the real-world decimal 
range to this integer range

Vint = round(Vfloat/s) + Z
S - Scale, a tiny positive decimal number that determines the step size between each integer value
Z - Zero-Point, the specific integer between -128 and 127 that represents exacly 0.0 in the real decimal world,


S = (MaxDec - MinDec) / 255

Z = round(-MinDec/S) + (-128)

Example for ReLu activation layer
MinDec = 0.0
MaxDec = 4.0

S = 0.015686
Z = -128